{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 14 "4.  The Euler " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "phi;" "6#
%$phiG" }{TEXT -1 176 "-function is defined as follows:   Let n be a p
ositive integer.  Let c be the number of  positive integers m there ar
e such that  m < n and  m and n are relatively prime.  Set " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "phi;" "6#%$phiG" }{TEXT -1 23 "(n) = c.  For example, \+
" }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "phi;" "6#%$phiG" }{TEXT -1 132 "(10) = 4, because th
ere are 4 positive integers less than 10 which are relatively prime to
 10  (namely:  1, 3, 7, 9).  For example, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "phi;" "6#%
$phiG" }{TEXT -1 143 "(14) =  6, because there are 6 positive integers
 less than 14 which are relatively prime to 14 (namely:  1, 3, 5, 9, 1
1, 13).    For example,  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "phi;" "6#%$phiG" }{TEXT -1 
134 "(15) = 8, because  there are 8 positive integers less than 15 whi
ch are relatively prime to 15 (namely:  1, 2, 4, 7, 8, 11, 13, 14).  \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 13 "    a
